<HEAD>Sentence Review for Convicted Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British government will review the life sentences of dozens of convicted terrorist prisoners in this <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province, officials said Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sentence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> will review the records of the Special Category inmates over the next six months and report back to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Secretary <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, his office reported. No reason was given for the review, but it appeared aimed at reducing tensions. The Special Category laws for suspected terrorists in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s sectarian warfare were introduced in 1972 after inmates staged a hunger strike at <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>'s Maze Prison, demanding to be treated as political prisoners. Their special privileges include political status and allow them to avoid prison work, wear their own clothes, have extra visits and food parcels and to live in isolated groups. In 1976, the Special Category status was ended for crimes committed after that date and in 1980 no more prisoners were admitted to the category. There are now 90 Special Category prisoners compared with 1,500 in 1975. There are 31 members of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, 27 of the mainly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and 32 from the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. All but five are serving life sentences or are detained on orders of the secretary of state. The predminantly <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to unite Protestant-dominated <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite the province with the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, which is overwhelmingly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>.
