<FIRST>r i PM-Mine-Survival     06-05 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine-Survival,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixty-Five Hours Underground _ A Reconstruction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For 65 hours, six men were trapped deep underground after a mine explosion in central <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Here, based on interviews with the survivors, mine officials, rescue workers and <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> news reports, is the story of their harrowing ordeal.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Huddled in the depths of a coal mine, six trapped miners take turns banging hammers together to signal rescuers. Their colleagues keep as still as possible to save precious air. `` Lie down, move as little as you can, drink the water in sips and breath as regularly as possible,'' veteran miner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> barks to his five-man crew. Toward the end of their 65-hour ordeal, their oxygen almost gone, the men hear a rescue worker screaming into his walkie-talkie: `` I see a light! I see two lights, I see three lights! I see people alive!'' The drama begins at 12:30 p.m. Wednesday, when a gas explosion traps 57 men in the mine in this town 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> and his five-man crew race toward the exit of the 500-foot-deep shaft. `` Maybe the blasting material storeroom blew up,'' the strapping, 36-year-old <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> says to himself. Out of the darkness, illuminated by the lights on the miners' helmets, appears the figure of a colleague staggering toward them <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> instantly recognizes the symptoms of the miners' dreaded foe _ carbon monoxide. He yells, `` Turn back, turn back!'' <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> and his crew head in the other direction. Other men nearby race toward the exit, into certain death from mounting levels of carbon monoxide that filled the tunnels. <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON>'s crew, wearing emergency masks containing about 45 minutes' worth of oxygen, rush to a point more than a mile from the blast site in the underground labyrinth of tunnels. Guided by the flames of cigarette lighters, they search for a space free of the deadly gas. Finally, the group finds air _ and a chance for survival. `` Be quiet, so you use up less oxygen,'' Gepperth orders. Huddled in the dark are: _ <ORGANIZATION> Egon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dehn </ORGANIZATION>, a bearded, 36-year-old father of two _ <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesner </PERSON>, 27, engaged to be married in August _ <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Roese </PERSON>, 33, married two years and the father of one _ <PERSON> Wilfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Doench </PERSON>, at 21 the youngest of the group Just four weeks earlier he'd walked away unharmed from a car wreck. _ <PERSON> Ahmet </PERSON> <PERSON> Batkan </PERSON>, 33 The Turkish immigrant has two children and his wife is expecting a third. The sixth man is <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON>, who is married. He often sports a diamond earring in his left ear. The men start shouting frantically into their walkie-talkies: `` One north 4-5, one north 4-5 six people.'' They hope to give rescue workers their precise location. Radio contact is made. But a radio operator orders the men to stop sending distress calls so he can try to reach other possible survivors. They try using the walkie-talkies again later but ca n't make contact The miners sit in the dark _ having turned off their miners' lamps to save batteries _ with their only nourishment a sandwich and mineral water Taking turns, they pound two hammers together in rhythmic blows to try to catch rescuers' attention. The banging goes on for nearly 65 hours. <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> tells his men to remember the `` Miracle of Lengede'' _ in which 11 miners were pulled to the surface two weeks after water flooded an iron mine in <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saxony </LOCATION> in 1963. Some of the men start to make last wills and testaments, but <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> gruffly tells them `` You do n't have to do that.'' <PERSON> Gepperth </PERSON> senses that the deadly carbon monoxide levels are advancing toward them, and the group retreats into the furthest recesses of the mine. Finally, their backs are against the wall. They can go no further and must stay in a prison-like space 6 -LCB- feet high and 8 feet wide. After waiting in vain Thursday, the men hear drilling on Friday. But it stops at mid-afternoon. <PERSON> Gesner </PERSON> says to himself: `` Have they forgotten us or something? Maybe they figure it's not worth it.'' He starts imagining he sees lights coming toward him, but there's no one there. They keep tapping, louder and louder. On Friday night, rescuers above think they've heard something. Hours pass. Then one of the trapped men screams: `` They've drilled a hole! At 4:21 a.m. Saturday, the rescue worker calls that he's found the men. A little more than an hour after they're discovered, the men are hoisted to the surface. After all 57 miners had been given up for dead, the `` Miracle of Borken'' had occurred.
</TEXT>
