<HEAD>Former Pennsylvania Congressman Dead At 97</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gildea </PERSON>, a Democrat who represented <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> from 1935 to 1939, died Sunday of cardiac arrest at age 97. <PERSON> Gildea </PERSON>, who died at the Manor Care nursing home in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, was a native of Coaldale, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. He made his home in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, before entering <ORGANIZATION> Manor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> four years ago. He was elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1934 and re-elected two years later. He was defeated by a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> opponent in 1938, and also was defeated in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> races in 1940 and 1950. <PERSON> Gildea </PERSON> had become a printing apprentice in 1905 and a newspaper publisher in 1910. He founded the <ORGANIZATION> Coaldale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION>, a weekly newspaper, and the <ORGANIZATION> Schuylkill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Record </ORGANIZATION>, a law publication. Survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Genevieve </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>.
