<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Peace     06-05 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Peace,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras, Sandinistas Closer Than Ever To Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government and U.S.-backed rebels are closer than ever to ending their 6 -LCB- - year war, but the last few steps to halt the fighting will be the most difficult The final measures are particularly crucial for the rebels, known as Contras, who may negotiate themselves out of existence in peace talks scheduled to resume Tuesday. The rebels do not have the political structure to survive as a separate organization on the Nicaraguan political scene. Their role likely will be taken over by the political parties already established in the country. Despite their rhetoric and posturing, the Contras and the government have been getting closer to a permanent agreement and have set a temporary truce that no one wants to break. The two sides signed a preliminary agreement on March 23 in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, a small village on the Costa Rican border. A 60-day cease-fire, which expired last Tuesday, has been extended until the two sides renew their discussions in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the Nicaraguan capital. During the last negotiating session, the government agreed to discuss some political reforms the Contra leadership considers essential. These include calls for political pluralism, equality before the law, the right to strike and a pluralistic electoral system. The reforms deal with definitions of `` democratization'' _ concepts that first led to the war, which has killed more than 26,000 people and ruined the country's economy. The Contra leadership feels the Sandinista regime is undemocratic, repressive and based on Marxism-Leninism. `` When it comes to definition of freedom of the press, civil rights, human rights, democracy, we are using the same words with different meanings. We are talking about two interpretations of reality based on different ideologies,'' said <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON>, leader of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` I am reasonably optimistic there will be an agreement,'' he said. `` It is not a question here of defeating the government at the negotiating table, but of finding a way to live together.'' <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> <PERSON> Leiva </PERSON>, a Contra adviser, said, `` The government must learn to live with what they term petite bourgeoisie. We can live with some of their leaders.'' <PERSON> Bayardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arce </PERSON>, deputy coordinator of the political commission of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` There are some in the opposition who have realized that there is political room for them here.'' <PERSON> Arce </PERSON> rejected charges that the government is trying to impose a communist state. `` We came to power talking about building socialism in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` But as we developed our struggle, we understood the national realities and we opted for a system of mixed economy with private and government property.'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, president of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, called the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> `` pragmatic and opportunistic'' but said there was little chance of a definite agreement on democratic reforms. `` Democratization is utopian in a country like ours where there has been no democracy for more than 60 years,'' he said. `` What we need is a continued process of democratic practices to test the political will of the government.'' `` If we do not agree on this,'' he said, `` the government will act unilaterally enacting electoral laws, and other changes that will make it look good abroad, while still talking to a divided opposition.'' The Sandinista government already has announced plans for municipal elections before the 1990 presidential elections. Opposition party leaders believe the Contras, as an organization, served a purpose in forcing the government to the negotiating table, but are at their weakest while negotiating an end to the war. <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said they will have to return and rejoin one of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s 14 political parties or form another party, `` which is the last thing <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> needs,'' <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Eloy </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguilar </PERSON> is The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>' bureau chief for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
