<HEAD>Scientist Says Crop Circles Caused By Whirlwinds, Not Flying
Saucers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mysterious circles of flattened crops in the British countryside over the centuries have been caused by stationary whirlwinds and not ghosts or UFOs, a scientist said Saturday. About 50 of the circles, with diameters of 10 to 100 feet, show up every summer usually in fields of long grass, barley, oats or wheat near hills, said tornado expert <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Meaden </PERSON>. Speaking at a conference in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, he dismissed speculation the circles were caused by flying saucers, helicopters flying upside down, supernatural beings or even herds of rotating hedgehogs, a small porcupine. `` Wind usually blows round both sides of a hill and merges smoothly round the other side,'' <PERSON> Meaden </PERSON> said. `` However, sometimes there is a gust on one side but not the other which creates vortices or sudden whirlwinds. These sink to the ground and flatten crops in a spiral.'' <PERSON> Meaden </PERSON> said the Tornado and <ORGANIZATION> Storm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where he works, investigated 150 crop circles over the past eight years.
