<HEAD>Four-year-old Dragged Into Pond By Alligator, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An alligator grabbed a 4-year-old girl walking along the shores of a pond and dragged her underwater Saturday as two horrified playmates watched, police said. The girl, who was not identified, remained missing after an extensive search, <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> deputies said. She was walking at the edge of the pond at the Gardens of Gulf Cove development at about 6:30 p.m. when the alligator lunged from the water, said sheriff's Capt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` The child was forcibly dragged into the water by the alligator,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` Our rescue units and dive teams have conducted an extensive search and the child has not yet been located.'' A neighbor, <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Triplett </PERSON>, said the girl's 6-year-old brother and a friend who is about 7 witnessed the attack. The children were walking a dog, she said. Another neighbor, <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, said when he heard the girl's mother screaming he went to the lake and saw a 10 - to-12-foot alligator surface twice about 20 yards away but saw nothing in its He said that the third time the gator came up, he saw a light-colored object in its mouth. Deputies and neighbors said gator prints and the child's shoe were found at the scene. Divers searched for three hours among the weeds in the freshwater lake but failed to find the alligator, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Six <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Game and <ORGANIZATION> Freshwater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> agents and several deputies and emergency workers also participated. The search was scheduled to continue Sunday, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said, adding that the child is still listed as missing and is not presumed dead.
