 Communist rebels ambushed a platoon of soldiers trying to retrieve a hijacked truck Sunday, killing 16 and wounding eight in one of the bloodiest rebel attacks this year, officials said. The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the troops managed to fight back and killed an undetermined number of rebels during the hour-long battle on an isolated mountain road. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> charged that unidentified European governments were indirectly financing communist rebels. <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> made the accusation on the third day of a conference among representatives of 13 Asian, European and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries that have won their freedom from dictators. A sketchy military report said 24 soldiers and militiamen were traveling on foot when they came under fire from an unknown number of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas outside <LOCATION> Silay </LOCATION> city, 300 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> and about 25 miles from <LOCATION> Bacalod </LOCATION>. The rebels fled when more troops backed by helicopter gunships and armored personnel carriers arrived, the report said. Residents of nearby villages evacuated their homes as troops continued to hunt the rebels after the battle, which began at 2 p.m., the officials said. Local radio reports said the ambushed soldiers were on their way to retrieve a truck loaded with fertilizer that rebels abandoned after hijacking it Saturday night. The truck belonged to one of the biggest sugar producing companies on <LOCATION> Negros </LOCATION> island. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is one of 12 Marxist groups that have been waging a 19-year insurgency in the <LOCATIO