<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates, increasingly concerned about political fallout from <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s legal problems, are beginning to call on the attorney general to leave President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Cabinet. At least four <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidates have urged <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> to resign and others have hinted they would like to see him go. Leading Republicans such as Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and White House staff chief <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> have conceded <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s troubles could severely damage <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> prospects this election year. But the attorney general has insisted he has done nothing wrong and will remain in office until he can `` set the record straight.'' Independent Counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> is expected to issue his report this month on <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s conduct. Sources familiar with the probe said the report would not recommend an indictment but would raise questions about <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s ethical conduct. In recent interviews <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has refused to say when he might leave office, but has ruled out a departure before his name is cleared `` because people would say there was something wrong.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s strongest defender in the administration is <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who has said that `` only a complete change of -LRB- <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s -RRB- character'' would prompt him to ask his old friend to resign. However, that view is not shared by many Republicans involved in tough election campaigns. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he met early last month with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, and the attorney general assured him he would do nothing to jeopardize the vice president's presidential campaign. In a recent inte