<HEAD>Environmentalist, Politician Pledge To Bring Wolves Back To
Yellowstone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An environmental leader and a Western politician have taken up the cause of the wolf, calling for its return to the wilds of the nation's first national park. They added their voices Saturday to that of the head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, who said that the howl of the wolf is `` the call, the music, of the West.'' Lined up in opposition are the majority of cattlemen and sheepmen in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> backed by <PERSON> Wymoning </PERSON>'s two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators and one representative. Speaking at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Utah </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>, president of the Defenders of Wildlife, urged national support for restoration of the wolf to Yellowstone National Park. The coalition, formed in 1983, consists of about 50 national, regional and local organizations that monitor management of the 2.5 million-acre park. Nearly all of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s wolf population was wiped out earlier this century by ranchers, farmers and bounty hunters. There have been a few sightings of lone wolves in a few Western states. A pack of wolves migrated across the Canadian border into <ORGANIZATION> Glacier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> two years ago, but left this year to go back into <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Efforts to revive the wolf population in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> have resulted in about 1,200 wolves there. Efforts to restart the red wolf population in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and Mexican wolf colonies in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> also are under way. Noting that the reintroduction of the gray wolf into <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> is endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> said: `` I am always offended when we politicians substitute our own value judgments for those of professional land managers. `` There is a theory among the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> congressional delegations that they own Yellowstone,'' said <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> said he introduced a bill in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> after discovering in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> park last fall that `` the wolf recovery program had been completely sidetracked by political interference.'' The bill would order the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to implement the Rocky Mountain Wolf Recovery Plan drawn up by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. It would re-establish wolves in the entire northern <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> region, including <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was clear to me when I introduced the bill that I could not pass it,'' said <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, `` but I hoped to expose the wolf to daylight. There is no predation problem with wolves. It is psychological _ the hatred of wolves.'' <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>, whose 80,000-member organization has reintroduction of wolves into <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> as a top priority, said, `` All Americans have a right to influence the course of events in Yellowstone National Park.'' <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> said restoring the wolves has `` enormous symbolic importance as well as ecological importance. ... -LRB- It -RRB- will be viewed as one of the major conservation accomplishments of the 1990s.'' <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> said Friday in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that he believes the reintroduction is inevitable. `` When that happens, people may never see a wolf,'' said <PERSON> Mott </PERSON>, `` but they will hear them howl. That is the call, the music, of the West. That quality is as important as a natural presence or a structure -LRB- within a park -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> urged the 300 people attending Saturday's meeting to rally support to force <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to hold hearings on the wolf reintroduction plan <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> said the next step would be an environmental impact statement on the proposal. He said a requested $ 200,000 federal appropriation is in danger of failing to get through the budget review process.
