<HEAD>Woman Sails Solo Nonstop Around World</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SYD1,4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 34-year-old Australian woman Sunday became the first woman to sail solo nonstop around the world when she navigated triumphantly into <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> harbor after a 189-day voyage. More than 10,000 people greeted <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON> at the harbor. She jumped out of the 36-foot sloop <PERSON> Blackmore </PERSON>'s First Lady and onto the dock for an emotional reunion with friends and family. Hundreds of small boats dotted the harbor to welcome her home from a trip she undertook to raise money for Australian children's charities Ms. <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> shipbuilder, told reporters that during the 23,000-mile easterly journey, `` I experienced real fear for the first time ever at sea.'' She said the worst seas came two days before she rounded <PERSON> Cape </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> at the southern tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> on Jan. 20. `` It was in mountainous seas breaking in huge waves _ just indescribable,'' she said. `` I thought the boat would roll right over and go down.'' But she said she enjoyed the experience. `` Who would n't be happy doing something they love for six uninterrupted months?'' she said. `` It was a personal challenge. ... I learned that I've got more endurance and determination than I ever thought I had.'' After leaving <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> harbor last Nov. 29, Ms. <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON> had no physical contact with other boats or people. She carried all the dried and canned food she needed for the trip. Her journey also was the fastest sailing trip around the globe by a woman. Ms. <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON> said she had not been lonely because she was regularly in radio contact with family members and the Australian media. `` With the state of modern communications equipment, I made a lot of friends along the way,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON> said she also had time to give up smoking, read books and listen to music. Among those at the harbor to meet Ms. <PERSON> Cottee </PERSON> were <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiner </PERSON>, premier of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON>, wife of Australian Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON>.
