necessary,'' but will not estimate their price, she said. He does not call for cuts in overall defense spending but would keep the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget `` stable'' for several years, financing his projects from cuts in Star Wars and other systems, she said. However, speaking to senior citizens in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in mid-May, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> suggested services for the elderly could be paid for from military cutbacks. `` Are we going to spend $ 6 billion on <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> and MX missiles on railroad cars, or are we going to build affordable housing for families of low and moderate income and the elderly?'' he asked. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opposes both the MX and Midgetman missile systems and is against plans to add two more aircraft carriers and the support ships that go with them. Although it is too late to stop the B-1 bomber program, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would not favor buying more B-1s if elected, said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, issues director for the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign. `` His point is we ca n't buy everything in the defense candy store,'' <PERSON> Edley </PERSON> said, `` that we have to make choices that really do advance our essential security needs. And he would emphasize our conventional strength.'' Ultimately, individual weapons systems may prove less important in shaping voters' judgments than feelings about the candidates' resolve and strength `` I think there's some real unease out there about where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would draw the line in the dust,'' <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said. In both the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> cites the need for agreement among other nations to stop hostilities. `` There's a feeling Governor <PERSON> D