<HEAD>`Back To Normal' As Full Phone Service Returns To Chicago Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Real estate agent <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> was burning up the phone lines again Sunday and <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Hector </PERSON>, expecting her third child any minute, felt calmer knowing she could reach out and touch someone in an emergency. Nearly a month after a May 8 fire damaged a switching station and left 35,000 customers in six western <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburbs without service for varying lengths of time, the Great Phone Outage came to a quiet end. At 12:01 a.m. Sunday, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> officials transferred the last 18,000 customers from the damaged, jury-rigged switch to a new, state-of-the-art digital unit. With as many as 250 employees often working around-the-clock, the company compressed what is normally a 50-week job into less than four weeks. `` It was a very good cutover, very uneventful,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>. `` Thank goodness. Any more problems and I might have hit the roof,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Hector </PERSON>, whose exchange was among the last of six to be transferred by <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>. `` Being without a reliable phone is like being without running water,'' she said. `` You never realize how important it is until it's gone.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> said she had spent much of the month in her car, running errands she normally would have taken care of by telephone. `` I could n't reach the other mothers in my children's pre-school classes for car pooling. I could n't call to make doctor's appointments for myself and then my own kids got sick,'' she said `` I just started showing up at the -LRB- doctors' -RRB- offices instead of making appointments. `` And then when I was home, I was anxious because I'm so far along -LRB- with the pregnancy -RRB-. Even so,'' she added, `` I think I'm going to miss some of those times when the phones were n't ringing off the hook. Not Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>. `` The phone is my lifeline,'' she said from her downtown <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> office. `` When it went down, so did my livelihood. There's only so much paperwork to catch up on, and that's how I justified the first couple of days without the phone. `` Then I went knocking on doors, driving around and leaving notes. But talk about inefficiencies. It was like a different country just a few miles from here where people's phones were working. `` I'd come over to show their house, and they'd tell me ` You'll have to come back later, we did n't have a chance to clean Why did n't you call us?' And I'd say, ` No phones.' And they'd look at me funny.'' Since the Mother's Day fire, phone service had been sporadic at best for Ms. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> and other Bell customers. About half were hooked up to the new system on May 26. With the remainder hooked up Sunday, the utility said things should be back to normal. `` Technically, this should be the end of it ... but there might be some little glitches that we will have to work out,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Hilary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. Although <PERSON> Illinois </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> promised rebates, several businesses were angry enough to file lawsuits charging the utility was negligent in failing to staff the switching station, which houses computerized equipment to connect local and long-distance calls. Firefighters reached the scene 82 minutes after an alarm registered at <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> monitoring station And Illinois Attorney General <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartigan </PERSON> filed a complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> seeking to have <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> pick up the tab for financial losses. But Sunday, at least, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> was savoring its accomplishments in returning the area to full service. `` We still have a lot of work to do, but it wo n't be the kind of feverish work we've been doing,'' said <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>. `` It was an extraordinary effort by all the people involved.''
