TION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. A group of Armenians then staged another rally outside the headquarters of the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON>, 39, was arrested by the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> secret police in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s capital, on March 25. He is the founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Self-Determination </ORGANIZATION>, an Armenian nationalist group. His wife, <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON>, 35, said that <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON>, who has served 17 years in prison, labor camp and internal exile for his political activities, was being held in a KGB isolation cell while charges against him were investigated. On March 19, <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON> told a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference that more than 70 people had died in anti-Armenian racial riots in the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> on Feb. 28. The Soviet government said 32 people were killed, and Mrs. <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON> said her husband had been accused of slandering the Soviet state. The riots grew out of ethnic tensions between Armenians and Azerbaijanis. Armenians have demanded that an Armenian-dominated area of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> be annexed to their republic. Mrs. <PERSON> Ayrikyan </PERSON>, her eyes red from crying, said there were reports her husband had a heart attack while in jail, but she said officials denied her any information about his health. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> accused the groups of staging a `` concert'' for Western reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to cover the 1,000 th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orthodox </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> and described <PERSON> Akrikyan </PERSON> as `` a dissident who has declared against the policy of the Soviet state more than once. `` The Criminal Code of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> has no such notion as a political prisoner,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. It accused `` extremist-minded'' Crimean Tatars of calling for the release of <PERSON> Sinaver </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadyrov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rishat </PERSON> <PERSON> Ablayev </PERSON> and said they were serving time `` for criminal offenses that have nothing to do with human rights.'' The Tatars, deported by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> as alleged wartime collaborators with the Germans, have been petitioning for years for the right to return to their Crimean homeland.
