bond, and Subs the 8th &amp; 9th grafs, beginning ``Yale President,''
with 5 grafs to update with details on reaction, background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> alumnus was charged with arson Sunday for allegedly torching makeshift shanties on the Ivy League campus that were built by students to protest South African apartheid, authorities said. Dr. <PERSON> Elwood </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracey </PERSON>, 56, of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, who apparently was visiting the university for alumni weekend, was stopped by a jogger near the blazing shanties, police said. He was released on $ 50,000 bond pending a Monday court appearance, police said. Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Charney </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> psychiatrist and class of 1968, said he saw a man running away from the fire as he was jogging across the campus Sunday morning. `` I yelled fire and ran after him,'' said <PERSON> Charney </PERSON>. `` He was in a tan suit, tie and his class button, which he took off as he ran.'' <PERSON> Charney </PERSON> said he caught up with the man in the courtyard of one of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s residential colleges, where the two had a political discussion about <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, apartheid and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s investment policies. `` In my opinion he acknowledged he had done it and he did it because he had strong feelings on this and felt alumni should have their say,'' <PERSON> Charney </PERSON> said. `` He also said he had given <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> a lot of money.'' The man told him he had worked in a hospital in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for three months, <PERSON> Charney </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Benno </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who had defended the university's decision to allow the shantytown to remain standing during a meeting Saturday with visiting alumni, denounced the arson as a `` lawless act of violence.'' `` To destroy them by an act of impulse is the antithesis of reason and order that is the essence of a university or any civilized community,'' he said in a statement. `` Beyond that, to set the shanties on fire furtively in the midst of an urban campus is an extremely dangerous thing to do.'' All that remained standing after the fire was a wooden shrine draped in the yellow, green and black colors of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and pasted with sheets of paper listing the names of 250 people who have been killed in the struggle against apartheid. `` It was a cowardly thing to do,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Morand </PERSON>, a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> graduate who helped build the shanties as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apartheid </ORGANIZATION> and now works in the university chaplain's office. The shanties were erected in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> administration building in April 1986 to protest apartheid and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> investment policies in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Officials ordered the shanties dismantled but allowed them to be rebuilt after students agreed to maintain them. <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> owns stock only in companies doing business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that subscribe to the <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Principles </PERSON>, a set of ethical guidelines aimed at improving the lives of South African blacks and ultimately at dismantling apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of racial separation. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Littell </PERSON>, a university spokesman, was unsure how much of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>'s stock portfolio was invested in companies doing business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. As of 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> had about $ 385 million invested in such companies.
