<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With lots of milk and corn flakes, <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> retained its title as the breakfast capital of the country by serving 32,697 people and beating the record set by <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. It was the third straight year that the city beat the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town for the bragging rights. `` We placed 35,076 servings of cereal on the mall, and 2,379 were returned for a total of 32,697 which leaves <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> the Breakfast Capital of the World,'' Breakfast Table Chairman <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Royal </PERSON> said Saturday. <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, home of <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> have swapped claims to putting out the largest breakfast since 1977. On May 14, <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> regained the title by feeding 31,279 people a pancake breakfast during its annual celebration of the founding of the city. `` Congratulations to <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> for topping us again,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, chairman of the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> event, said Saturday. `` I was hoping for rain but we did n't get it. We feel we can outdo those numbers and that will be our aim next year. `` We are not giving up,'' he said. `` We can do those numbers even if pancakes are more difficult than pouring milk.'' During the breakfast battles, the rules have changed. It started out as a challenge to put out the longest table. But the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> said a city in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> once sat 6,400 people at a table 7,908 feet long _ just shy of a mile and a half. That was more than <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> officials could stomach, so they changed the name of their contest from the `` World's Longest Breakfast Table'' to the `` World's Largest Breakfast Event.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This little piggy going to market wanted to be the one that stayed home, and its break for freedom at a city intersection caused a police chase aided by broom and lasso. The 250-pound pig, part of a load of hogs being taken to Granite City Livestock Sales, jumped off the back of its owner's truck at a busy street corner and trotted off to a residential area. `` He must have climbed on the backs of the other pigs in the truck, then he leaped out,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, a witness who helped capture the animal after its Thursday morning getaway. `` It's remarkable for a pig to walk away from a jump like that without broken legs. He must have jumped about four feet,'' <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON> said. The pig ended up in the back yard of <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Proell </PERSON>. `` He came down the alley and then wandered up to my fence. The cop was right behind him,'' said <PERSON> Proell </PERSON>, who was watering his lawn. `` I figured I could guide him with a broom and keep him against the fence,'' <PERSON> Proell </PERSON> said. `` I was talking to him, trying to keep him in this corner.'' After police officers failed to grab the hog, <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON> managed to lasso it and put it in his truck. He took it to the livestock market and returned it to owner <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Steffenhagen </PERSON> of <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, who had driven off unaware of his hog's exit. The athletic animal was sold at auction.
