<HEAD>Legislators Propose Registering Prostitutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> legislators asked the government to officially register prostitutes to ensure they receive regular medical checkups, it was reported Sunday. The parliamentarians, members of the 100-seat assembly, made the request during a meeting to discuss health care services, according to the state-owned Sunday Mail newspaper. Registration and regular medical examinations for prostitutes would curb the spread of sexually-transmitted diseases and acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the newspaper quoted the parliamentarians as saying. AIDS, for which there is no cure, attacks the body's immune system and prevents it from fighting infection. The majority of those affected worldwide are drug addicts and homosexuals, but in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the disease is spread mostly though heterosexual contacts.
