<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said Sunday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be to blame if peace talks with Nicaraguan rebels scheduled to begin on Tuesday fail to produce a permanent cease-fire. `` We hold the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government responsible for what happens in these meetings'' with the Contras, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said after meeting with agricultural, industrial, health and education workers. Leaders of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella organization, are scheduled to hold talks with government officials June 7-9 in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. It would be the fourth session held in the Nicaraguan capital to negotiate terms of a permament truce to the 6 -LCB- - year-old civil war <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> also said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration would be at fault `` if in this meeting the Contras do not agree to lay down their arms.'' The rebels, trained, funded and supplied by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, began their war to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government in 1981. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said in an interview after his speech that his government would offer `` no variations'' to its peace proposal submitted during the last round of negotiations held May 26-28. The Contras turned down a government proposal for a 30-day cease-fire extension and a plan for delivering humanitarian aid to rebel units athered in truce zones. Both sides have agreed to hold their fire at least until the end of this week's talks. The government agreed to discuss some of the Contras' demands for political changes they say would bring about democratization in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Those include freedom of the press, the lifting of all political restrictions, separation of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> from the army and the government, constitutional changes and electoral and judicial reforms. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said on Sunday the rebel delegation would be permitted to visit leaders of the internal opposition and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> during its stay in the capital. The Contra delegation planned to travel to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> on Monday to prepare for the talks, said a rebel spokesman in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Sunday. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
