<HEAD>Socialists Projected To Win Majority In Legislative Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with new figures. Pickup 4th graf
pvs ``State-run Antenne...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Socialists and conservatives virtually split the popular vote in Sunday's first round of elections for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. French television projected President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s Socialists will win the most seats. Based on 97 percent of the ballots counted, the Socialists had 37.4 percent of the vote when the counting was stopped late Sunday. The conservative Rally for the Republic and center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, which backed the same candidates, garnered 37.7 percent. The Communists took 11.2 percent and the rightist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> 9.7 percent, with the rest going to minor parties. Counting was to resume Monday. State-run Antenne 2 network's projections gave the Socialists between 310 and 330 seats in the 577-seat assembly. It said the Rally for the Republic and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> would win 230-250 seats and the Communists 10-20, with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> shut out. In predicting the makeup of the new assembly _ the lower and more powerful house of Parliament _ the television network projected the final outcome for all districts including areas that will have runoff elections next Sunday. Candidates needed at least 50 percent of the vote in the first round to win a seat in the legislature. In districts where there was no winner in the first round, candidates had to receive at least 12.5 percent of the first-round votes to be eligible for the June 12 runoff. There is inevitable pressure on those coming in lower than second to drop out and support one of the two frontrunners in the runoff. This system was expected to hurt the smaller parties but help the Socialists. In 1986, before the new system was adopted, seats were assigned on the basis of the percentage of votes won by lists of candidates. Projections showed 65.5 percent of the 38 million people eligible to vote cast ballots _ one of the lowest turnouts in recent years. That compares with 78.5 percent in the March 1986 legislative election and 81.4 percent in the first round of the presidential election April 24. Polls had predicted a wider Socialist advantage. `` It's an encouraging result, but we have to consolidate it,'' said former conservative Finance Minister <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Balladur </PERSON>. `` Victory is possible if we unite. We have a week to convince all those who do not want to give a majority to the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.'' Polls also predicted the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> _ which each won 35 seats in the last election _ would fare badly because of the winner-take-all voting system reinstituted two years ago. The election came less than a month after <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> defeated former Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, a conservative, with a solid 54 percent of the vote. Conservatives controlled the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> from 1986 until <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> dissolved it after his re-election. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> had said during his presidential campaign he wanted to work with the existing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and open the Cabinet to non-Socialists from the political center. New Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> formed a government with no notable presence from other parties, however, and <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> called the election. The Sunday newspaper Journal du Dimanche noted in a front-page editorial that despite the importance of the election for the future, `` the campaign gave rise only to boredom or indifference.'' Few issues were debated. The Socialists declared they were ready to institute a guaranteed minimum wage, to be paid for in part with a special tax on large fortunes. Such a tax was abolished by the right in 1986. Socialists continued with <PERSON> Mittterrand </PERSON>'s `` opening'' theme through the campaign, but most politicians of the right and center-right viewed the idea as little more than an invitation for them to become Socialist.
</TEXT>
