<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A panel of former judges on a commission of inquiry arranged by two television companies said Sunday there was insufficient evidence to determine if <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> committed war crimes as a German army officer. The panel issued its decision on the Austrian president and former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> general-secretary after hearing nine days of testimony in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in April. Witnesses included officers who served with <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> in the German army in World War II and survivors of concentration camps and civilian massacres. The inquiry was paid for by <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, both of which screened a 3 -LCB- - hour program program Sunday night that included some of the testimony and the decision by the jurists `` We conclude unanimously that the evidence which has been put before us is not enough to make it probable that Lt. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> committed any of the war crimes alleged against him in this inquiry,'' the panel said. The five judges also found `` lapses and aberrations of memory such as Dr. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> seems to have had about his services in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> are not in themselves evidence of guilt.'' But the commission said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> `` must have known'' about German plans to shoot captured Italian officers. The former judges who participated in the inquiry came from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has been shunned by many countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has barred him from entering the country, because of allegations about his actions as an army lieutenant in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> from 1942 to 1945. A historians' commission appointed by the Austrian government that investigated the allegations said in February that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was `` in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION>, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. But it did not support allegations that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was involved in committing atrocities. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied any wrongdoing. The panel that participated in the television inquiry was headed by a retired <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge, Sir <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON>. Other members were <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hufstedler </PERSON>, a former circuit judge for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, and West German <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubner </PERSON>, Swede <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Petren </PERSON> and Canadian <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> _ all retired appeals court judges.
