<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government and U.S.-backed rebels are closer than ever to ending their 6 -LCB- - year war, but the last few steps to halt the fighting will be the most difficult The final measures are particularly crucial for the rebels, known as Contras, who may negotiate themselves out of existence in peace talks scheduled to resume Tuesday. The rebels do not have the political structure to survive as a separate organization on the Nicaraguan political scene. Their role likely will be taken over by the political parties already established in the country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> voters, who sparked a nationwide taxpayer revolt with Proposition 13 a decade ago, are being asked in a series of ballot measures whether they are having some second thoughts. Although gloomy predictions of fiscal disaster remain largely unrealized since the measure cut property taxes by $ 7 billion, or an average of 57 percent, Proposition 13 has had its visible effects. The public increasingly pays for services that once were free, including parks and recreation programs. Public grounds look scruffier than they did 10 years ago as officials have cut back on maintenance. State bailouts and creative funding schemes are credited with keeping most local governments afloat since the measure was approved June 6, 1978, but many agree that schools and rural counties have suffered under the cuts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
