<HEAD>Economic Summits First Began in 1975</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economic Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's leading industrialized democracies have held annual economic summits since 1975 when leaders first gathered for informal talks at <LOCATION> Rambouillet </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The original six participants were the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> joined the group in 1976 and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> was invited to participate in 1977. Summit sites rotate among member nations. Meetings have been held in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, 1976; <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, 1977; <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, 1978; <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, 1979; <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, 1980; <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> and Montebello, 1981; <LOCATION> Versailles </LOCATION>, 1982; <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION>, 1983; <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, 1984; <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, 1985; <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, 1986; and <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, 1987.
</TEXT>
