<DOCNO> AP880605-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DisgruntledInvestors Bjt   06-05 0913</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disgruntled Investors, Bjt,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Consider Giving More Power to Investors in Stock Disputes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first instinct of thousands of investors shocked by the almost instant evaporation of their money in the October stock market crash was to sue their brokers. It was then that many got a second shock: They discovered they had signed away their right to go to court. Fine print buried in most brokerage firms' paperwork requires customers to settle disputes through an arbitration hearing sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> or other market organization. Arbitration, because it is cheaper and faster than suing, is a good deal for many customers, particularly those who claim damages of $ 50,000 or less. But there is only a limited right to appeal and some investors _ big losers and those whose brokers' actions were especially egregious _ may be better off in court. And even investors likely to recover all or part of their losses in arbitration may not want to give up the option to sue before they know the nature of the dispute. Big institutional investors have always had the clout to negotiate contracts with securities firms, but a survey earlier this year by the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> found that individual investors have little choice. Of 65 firms, handling 90 percent of all customer accounts, virtually all require arbitration, particularly for customers who borrow money from the firm through margin accounts or trade in risky stock options. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, concerned that mandatory arbitration adds to the popular perception that the markets are stacked against the individual, are hoping to restore customers' right to choose Three states _ <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> _ are also considering proposals to restrict arbitration clauses, according to the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of state regulators. The issue is becoming more acute as the number of arbitration cases soars because of the crash and because the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last June upheld the legality of mandatory arbitration clauses. The association said that the number of cases quintupled from 800 in 1980 to 4,100 last year and could climb above 6,000 this year. At a recent <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> hearing, Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said that he believes arbitration offers `` a fine opportunity for cost saving,'' but as a matter of fairness, firms ought to be barred from denying service to a customer who does n't want to sign an arbitration clause. `` I fail to see why we should deny access to the securities markets to one who is unwilling to waive their dispute -LRB- into arbitration -RRB- in advance,'' he said. Commodity brokers are already forbidden to force customers to arbitrate. The commission, for two hours last Wednesday, debated whether to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to extend the ban to securities brokers. But, after last-minute lobbying by the securities industry, it postponed the decision for a month to give firms a chance to press their opposition. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON>, general counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> are trying to craft a solution to a problem that does not exist. The system is fair; only a very small percentage of complaints to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> are about arbitration, he said. And, he said, the market organizations are moving to put in place a number of changes recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> last September. They include education for arbitrators and guidelines designed to keep people with industry ties from serving in the `` public'' slots on arbitration panels. Moreover, firms are not denying customers access to the market, <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON> said. Most do n't require customers with cash accounts to sign arbitration clauses, he said, and customers who want to borrow money on margin can go to banks or elsewhere. The proposal before government officials `` essentially says to a broker-dealer you no longer have a right as a businessman to make a judgment to control your legal expenses through the use of arbitration,'' he said. `` It makes no sense to force disputes ... into a court system where it takes five to seven years to get a case out and nobody wins except the trial attorneys,'' he said. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> appears to have the backing of a majority of his five-member commission. <PERSON> Aulana </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> is firmly in his corner and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said he would have to be persuaded to vote against the proposal. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is proceeding on its own. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on finance scheduled a hearing on the issue for Thursday. Rep. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, D-Va., is preparing legislation that would require firms to present arbitration clauses under a heading with large type and on a separate sheet of paper Firms would be forbidden to reject customers who decline to sign the clause or charge them an added fee for refusing. <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said he reviewed one form used by several firms and found the arbitration clause in small print in a section with an unrelated headline. `` Even a very careful reading of the form might not reveal the binding arbitration language. I was looking for it and it took me quite a while,'' he said. `` That to me is improper. If a person is going to surrender his right to a trial in court, the person should do so with full knowledge and, secondly, it should be a purely voluntary decision,'' he said.
