<HEAD>Consummate Washington Insider Heads New Commission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The health of the economy is at risk. The federal debt is swelling, and the politicians are gridlocked. What's a nation to do? Call in the bureaucrat! That may sound a little odd, but a consummate <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> insider was required to direct the new bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in its mission to cut the deficit. The commission director not only needed a thorough knowledge of the budget, but had to be trusted by both sides of the political spectrum. And, perhaps most important, someone was needed with skill in handling giant egos. Enter <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> of the president's <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>. Described by a colleague as `` the quintessential staff person,'' <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> first worked at <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> in 1961, before it was <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>, when it was just the Bureau of the Budget. He's made a career of public service, mostly at <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> but also overseas as an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. At <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>, he has worked for Democrats and Republicans, <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON>. Now <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> has to use that experience to stay in the background but still guide the commission members to a conclusion on the deficit by their self-imposed deadline of December 21st. The common wisdom in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is that the commission would provide political `` cover'' for a tax increase and some spending cuts, leading <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already to pre-emptively say he wo n't support it But <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> says predicting the commission's actions would be a mistake, and he wo n't try to read the minds of members who include <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> and former Secretary of Defense <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON>. `` If you have n't decided what time you're going home tonight, I ca n't forecast it. And if I do, I'm a fool,'' he said in an interview last week. With the commission just starting up, <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON>'s major effort is to educate the members, most of whom have little exposure to the federal budget. His staff is creating a computer game, where members can try out different policies and instantly receive a computation of their effect on the deficit. The co-chairmen of the commission are <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer and Democratic party power broker, and <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> who now heads the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>. It will be their job to plead and cajole the panel toward a consensus, with <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> smoothing whatever path they choose. The deficit commission is frequently compared in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to the so-called <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> commission, led by now-Federal <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, whose recommendations led to the 1983 financial revamping of the Social Security program. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has even moved into the townhouse across from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> where the <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> group was based. However, <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> says this mission is different. Social Security was facing a crisis, and there was the threat that the checks would not go out unless action was taken. While most economists agree that the federal deficit, $ 150 billion last year, is bad for the economy, its effects are more difficult to single out. `` If we were able to say that on the 13th of March, 1989, the stock market will drop -LRB- unless action is taken -RRB-, then we've got a deal,'' <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mathiasen </PERSON> agrees that perhaps the most important factor in whether the commission succeeds will be the attitude of the next president-elect. Before taking office, the next president can appoint two more commission members. The hope of the panel is to prevent its work from getting snarled in presidential politics, but then quickly make its recommendations to help build a consensus on how to reduce the deficit for the next president and next <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to enact.
