<FIRST>r f AM-CalSpending     06-05 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cal Spending,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposition 13 Still Being Felt 10 Years Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> voters, who sparked a nationwide taxpayer revolt with Proposition 13 a decade ago, are being asked in a series of ballot measures whether they are having some second thoughts. Although gloomy predictions of fiscal disaster remain largely unrealized since the measure cut property taxes by $ 7 billion, or an average of 57 percent, Proposition 13 has had its visible effects. The public increasingly pays for services that once were free, including parks and recreation programs. Public grounds look scruffier than they did 10 years ago as officials have cut back on maintenance. State bailouts and creative funding schemes are credited with keeping most local governments afloat since the measure was approved June 6, 1978, but many agree that schools and rural counties have suffered under the cuts. So on Tuesday, voters in 26 of the state's 57 counties will decide whether to raise sales and other taxes in their areas to pay for highways, schools, libraries, jails and other services that were threatened or eliminated by Proposition 13. At the same time, two rival statewide measures _ Proposition 71 and <ORGANIZATION> Proposition </ORGANIZATION> 72 _ will ask voters whether to ease a constitutional spending limit and provide more money for schools or highways. The spending limit, in the form of an initiative written by tax-cut pioneer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gann </PERSON>, was approved in a special election nine months after Proposition 13. It requires that spending be strictly tied to increases in population and the nationwide cost of living. The two new measures would alter that limit. Proposition 71, whose main supporter is state schools Superintendent <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Honig </PERSON>, would permit additional funding for schools. Proposition 72, written by <PERSON> Gann </PERSON> himself, would allow new money for highway construction. Republican Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, grappling with a $ 1.1 billion budget deficit, opposes both measures. Other issues on Tuesday's ballot include a proposal to empower the state to quarantine AIDS victims and local measures that could close the <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear power plant and divide <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> into two. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> also is holding a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> primary, along with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, in addition, is having primaries in both parties for governor. Proposition 13 _ whose war cry was quickly picked up by voters in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and other states _ decreed that property tax assessments be rolled back immediately to 1975-76 levels. It limited annual property taxes to 1 percent of the market value and stipulated that assessed values, and thus taxes, could be increased by only 2 percent annually until a property is sold. Then the new owner's property tax bill starts at 1 percent of the purchase price. The measure also made it extremely difficult for local school districts to raise property taxes, requiring that voters approve any new taxes by a two-thirds margin. The year before Proposition 13 was approved, local governments received $ 10.3 billion in property taxes, according to the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equalization </ORGANIZATION>. In 1978-79, the first year after Proposition 13, that figure plunged to $ 4.9 billion. The immediate crunch was eased by the state, which contributed $ 4.4 billion in 1978-79, but over the years that state support has worn thin. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Houx </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said there is little money for vocational education, after-school sports and fine arts programs for the state's 4.5 million students. `` It's not like it was before, when the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> could raise money locally, and for the big bucks we could go to the voters and ask for approval with a simple majority,'' said <PERSON> Houx </PERSON>. Many school libraries have been closed or forced to curtail their hours. More than $ 11 billion is needed for new school construction throughout the state, and deferred maintenance costs are approaching $ 150 million, <PERSON> Houx </PERSON> said. The city of <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION>'s street repair unit faces $ 60 million in deferred maintenance costs that built up in the eight years after Proposition 13 passed. In 1986, residents approved a 15-year sales tax increase to pay for street maintenance and repair. An increasing number of residents of <LOCATION> Humboldt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in the northwestern section of the state, are driving on gravel as officials give up on maintaining many deteriorating roads. <LOCATION> Shasta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, with 125,000 residents, replaced a 73-bed public hospital that also served several neighboring counties with a clinic.
</TEXT>
