<SECOND>AM-Harvard-Wall Street,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business School Seeks To De-emphasize Wall Street Careers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> is making it clear that it wants a smaller proportion of its graduates to head for Wall Street investment banking. The business school reported last week that 15 percent of its current crop of graduates had been hired by major securities firms, compared to about 30 percent in 1987. `` We do n't want investment banking to be the be-all and end-all of a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MBA </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, the business school's director of placement School officials said they began shifting the emphasis away from investment banking even before last October's stock market crash. `` There was a real concern that we were being typecast as a school for investment bankers and consultants,'' said Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, a technology management expert. `` Our mission is to train general managers. We were afraid of losing our heritage.'' The changes at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> included improving its manufacturing faculty, changing its admissions policies to de-emphasize financial skills and choosing fewer people from Wall Street apprenticeship programs. A decade ago, just 8 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> graduates went into investment banking while consulting was the job of choice, attracting 22 percent. But the bull market that began in 1982 and the merger-and-acquisition binge that started soon afterward shifted the balance. In 1978, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> students could expect to earn roughly the same starting salary on Wall Street as in manufacturing. By 1987, Wall Street salaries were about 10 percent higher than those in manufacturing, but with bonuses figured in, the gap was closer to 50 percent. There were complaints that American manufacturing was being shortchanged. `` We now have a group coming out of business schools, going to Wall Street and contributing nothing to the efficiency of American industry, nothing to its productivity,'' retired <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> said in 1987. Last March, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> hired <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheelwright </PERSON>, a specialist in manufacturing, from <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. But officials said the changes may still not funnel more bright young graduates into the production sector. `` We can do all the pushing and cajoling we want,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, `` but if companies do not offer jobs at competitive salaries, the students will not go that way.'' `` I tell students that tomorrow's chief executive officers will be the ones who solve our production problems,'' said <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurow </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Sloan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Thurow </PERSON> said his message is not taking root yet and that the business school students still consider manufacturing a second-class profession.
