<HEAD>Saudis Report Big Trade Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> posted a $ 2.4 billion trade surplus last year, more than seven times the 1986 surplus, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said in a report Sunday. The 1986 surplus totaled $ 360,000, said excerpts of the report that were circulated by the official <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The big increase followed a major effort by the Saudis to diversify their economy away from dependence on oil revenues. They have developed agriculture, wheat and food products for export, as well as domestic consumption. The ministry report said exports totalled $ 22.56 billion last year and imports $ 20 billion. In 1986 exports totaled $ 19.24 billion with imports pegged at $ 18.88 billion, the report said. The Saudi news agency did not provide any breakdown of export figures and gave only a partial list of import statistics. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> report showed 81.2 percent of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s imports last year came from 15 countries, headed by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> Imports from <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> states last year increased by 8.6 percent over the preceding year, while imports from non-Arab Islamic states increased by 9.8 percent. The oil-rich kingdom's major import categories all rose last year, at least in value. The agency report only cited import values. They were listed as foodstuffs and livestock, which increased by 7.2 percent in value, beverages and tobacco by 12 percent, raw materials by 21.6 percent, vegetable oils and fats by 10.4 percent, machinery and transport equipment by 2.1 percent, furniture, clothing and shoes by 5.7 percent. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> sits on almost one-third of the world's proven oil reserves, but has been hard hit by a weak world oil market since the early 1980s. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has a population of around 12 million, including an estimated 3 million expatriate workers.
