<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three years ago, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> set out to grab a share of the retail beer market _ a very small share. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> owns one of a growing number of micro-brewers _ small companies that make small amounts of beer, mostly heavier brews. Sales doubled last year, and <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, 29, hopes his <ORGANIZATION> Kalamazoo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> will break even or even turn a profit this year. He began his business on $ 39,000 borrowed from friends in a former plumbing supply store with a 15-gallon pot and stove. While business has picked up a bit, everything still is done by hand. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> once said his brewery was the smallest in the country. He now produces about 1,400 barrels of ale annually, which may bring in about $ 250,000 in sales this year, mushrooming from the $ 65,000 in sales last year. The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewers </ORGANIZATION> estimates there are 80 micro-breweries nationwide, up from 46 two years ago. Some speculate that the popularity of the breweries increased as people began looking for alternatives to light, highly carbonated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beers. Despite the growth of these small operations, major brewers are n't foaming about competition. Last year, less than 0.1 percent of the 187 million barrels of beer were consumed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> came from small brewers. `` That's not a number that one takes very seriously,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinman </PERSON>, publisher of the Beer Marketers Insight newsletter. `` It would take tremendous growth before the micro-breweries have any effect on the industry.'' One of the big problems for little breweries is delivery. Beer that is n't pasteurized goes bad without refrigeration _ a problem that drove <ORGANIZATION> Chelsea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, out of business several years ago. The failure rate for small breweries is pretty high, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendel </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fermentation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> `` About one brewery in five closes down,'' he said. `` Some last four or five years, and some close in a matter of weeks.'' Meantime, <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> keeps pumping out his brew with an eye toward some mechanization. He bought a bottling machine, but it is in need of repair. He hopes to raise another $ 100,000 for more equipment. `` It's very difficult to make money when you're washing bottles by hand,'' he said. `` We're just starting to get to the break-even point, but it's been a real crap shoot.''
</TEXT>
