<FIRST>r f AM-MouthLightning     06-05 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mouth Lightning,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Professor To Present Study of Light Emitted By Wintergreen Candy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even party tricks can have scientific interest, and a <ORGANIZATION> Towson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> chemistry professor will tell a conference this week about the tiny sparks that appear when you bite wintergreen candy in the dark. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweeting </PERSON> has been researching the phenomenon _ technically known as triboluminescence _ for five years, crushing candies in her laboratory and carefully measuring the dim flashes. She'll present her findings at the third <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. She admits she also sometimes ducks into closets to crunch the candy and watch the bluish sparks of `` mouth lightning.'' Substances that flash when they're rubbed, crushed or broken include sugar, salt, quartz and human bones. Triboluminescence, a name drawn from the Greek word `` tribein'' meaning `` to rub,'' was first reported by Sir <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON> in 1605. Ms. <PERSON> Sweeting </PERSON>, 46, took advantage of recent technological advances in highly accurate measuring instruments to confirm basic theories about triboluminescence developed in the 1930s and to add more accurate knowledge about the range of light emitted. She drew upon wintergreen candy studies conducted in the 1930s by <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researcher <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>. She said the tiny sparks are created because, when sucrose sugar crystals fracture under pressure, positive and negative electrical charges separate. Voltage builds up until electrons leap across the fracture and the discharge makes nitrogen molecules in the air emit a tiny burst of light. That light comes mainly in the invisible ultraviolet region of the spectrum. But when wintergreen is added, the light becomes visible as blue sparks because wintergreen molecules glow when excited by the flash of the initial spark, a tiny reaction that ends in milliseconds. Although he has not seen the results to be presented in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Zink </PERSON>, a professor of chemistry at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> who furthered the research in the early 1980s, said he did n't find the mechanism to be quite as Ms. <PERSON> Sweeting </PERSON> described it. He said its behavior could vary from crystal to crystal. Ms. <PERSON> Sweeting </PERSON> said she stands by her research, which was `` very carefully done on the same batch of crystals.'' `` I guess most of the scientific community would think this is not real important,'' she said. `` But it's fundamental knowledge of crystals, how energy flows in and out of molecules, and there are going to be practical applications down the road.'' As an example, she suggested that a triboluminescent film could could be used to coat parts of orbiting satellites so that Earth-based instruments could detect any light emissions produced when the materials are put under unexpected stress.
</TEXT>
